{center}
{subhead}Hints &  Tips{def}{p}
Article by Mark Tierno
{left}
{pp}
{bold}PROGDIR:{nobold}{p}
A built-in dynamic assignment, it will work in any requester or within
any program.  It's an assignment that always points to the directory
from which the program was started from.  Any file or directory requesters
launched by a given program can use PROGDIR: to go to the directory that
it's calling program came from.
{pp}
{bold}SetPatch Commandline Options:{nobold}{p}
In case you still aren't sure what all the Commandline options for
Setpatch are, then here they are...{p}
NOROMUPDATE/S .. doesn't install the ROM update at all.{p}
DISABLEROMMODULES/K .. accepts a comma separated list (no spaces) of module names and disables them.{p}
SKIPROMUPDATES/S .. skips selected update modules in the ROM update file. It also accepts a comma separated list of module names.{p}
KILLUPDATE/S .. removes all the kicktags SetPatch had installed.{p}
FORCEUPDATE/S .. will install updates even though something has been previously installed.{p}
WAITFORVALIDATE/S .. SetPatch will wait for all volumes to be validated now before rebooting. The DosList will be checked once a second.{p}
{pp}
{bold}HDToolBox Tooltypes:{nobold}{p}
And finally, here are the tooltypes for HDToolBox.{p}
ASKDEVICE=YES ... "TRUE" or left blank is also valid else "NO"{p}.
DEVICE=devicename ... name of device{p}
SCSI_DEVICE_NAME=devicename ... same as DEVICE; may be used for compatibility reasons.{p}
WIDESCSI=YES ... set for wide SCSI adapters; arguments same as "ASKDEVICE".{p}
MFSAVEPATH=pathname ... where to save mount files and filesystems to; defaults to SYS:{p}
